<b>Comparative Genomics</b> <I>Arabidopsis</I> is a small part of our genetic
diversity, and is part of a new research center here <a href="http://www.evolutionarygenomics.dk/comparativegenomics/">
www.evolutionarygenomics.dk/comparativegenomics
</a>.
<br><b>Disease Resistance</b>-  We use functional genomic approaches to study
genes mediating physiological and developmental processes. One mutant we
have used as a tool is an insertion line exhibiting recessive dwarfism due
to transposon inactivation of the MAP Kinase 4 gene. Current work includes:
analyses of MPK4 substrates including MKS1, transcriptomic analyses of downstream
MPK4 effectors, and the relation of MPK4 and homologs to other signaling
pathways.<br>
<b>Programmed Cell Death</b>- Another insertion produced the Accelerated Cell
Death 11 mutant (acd11) that exhibits characteristics of animal apoptosis
monitored by flow cytometry, and acd11 constitutively expresses defense-related genes
that accompany the hypersensitive response normally triggered by avirulent pathogens.
Current work includes: selection and analyses of suppressors and effectors of PCD, analyses
of ACD11 interacting proteins, and functions of ACD11 homologs in plants
and animals. 
<br><b>Hormonal control & bioluminescent transgenes</b>- We also use fusion genetic
strategies to identify signaling components involved in the regulation of
gene expression in response to JA or gibberellin (GA). Towards this end,
 promoter sequences of  the 1) JA-inducible LOX1,  2) GA- responsive GASA1, or
3) GA-repressible GA20Oxidase (GA5) were fused to both the E. coli GUS and
firefly luciferase (LUC) reporters. These constructs were transfered to
plants and their expression shown to be appropriately regulated by the
hormones. These plants were then mutagenized and progeny screened for
trans-signaling mutants that inappropriately express both reporters and
the endogenous GASA1, GA5 or LOX1 genes.  These screens and genes involved
in GA and JA signaling identified by positional cloning. 
