<p>
<b>SNARE proteins in disease resistance</b>
<br>
We have identified roles of the <I>Arabidopsis</I> syntaxin genes <I>SYP121</I> and
<I>SYP122</I> in disease resistance. Through our discovery of the mutants <I>pen1-1</I>
and <I>pen1-2</I>, we identified <I>SYP121 (=PEN1</I>) to be required for penetration resistance
against powdery mildew fungi (Collins et al., 2003; Assaad et al., 2004; Zhang et al., 2007).
During penetration resistance, observed when fungi attack directly through the plant
epidermis cell wall, a local apposition (often termed &#239;&#191;&#189;papilla&#239;&#191;&#189;) is formed on the
inner side of the cell wall at the site of penetration. We predict that processes
of this papilla formation are <I>SYP121</I>-dependent (Assaad et al., 2004).
<br>We subsequently described that simultaneous mutation of the genes <I>SYP121</I> and
<I>SYP122</I> causes the plants to develop a lesion mimic phenotype, mediated by strong
activation of several defence signalling pathways. This shows that <I>SYP121</I> and <I>SYP122</I>
 are negative regulators of these signalling pathways, which includes the salicylic acid (SA),
jasmonic acid (JA) and ethylene (ET)-pathways, as well as a pathway leading to a
&#239;&#191;&#189;hypersensitive response&#239;&#191;&#189; (HR)-like defence that provides complete resistance to the
powdery mildew fungus, <I>Erysiphe cichoracearum</I> (Zhang et al., 2007). 

