<p>
<b>Molecular analysis of cold acclimation
</b>
<br>Our general aim is to characterize components in 
signaling networks involved in activation of low temperature 
responsive genes. Two different approaches are being used to 
obtain knowledge of the components involved in signaling and 
their role in the signaling network.
<UL type=1>
<LI>Isolation and characterization of signal transduction 
mutants from T-DNA activation tagged mutant collection:
<br>We have generated a large collection of mutant lines with 
random T-DNA insertions generated with an activation tag 
vector in transgenic 
<I>Arabidopsis
</I> exhibiting stress induced luciferase production.
<br>
<LI>Candidate gene approach
<br>Available expression data concerning large number of 
<I>Arabidopsis
</I> genes allows us to identify genes, whose products are 
likely to be involved in low temperature signaling. These 
genes will be used directly to assess their role in 
activation of low temperature responsive genes and 
development of freezing tolerance by either overexpressing 
them or inhibiting their expression by RNAi strategy. 
</UL>
</p>

