<p>
<b>Plants and heavy metal tolerance mechanisms
</b>
<br>
The main object of genetic and proteomic profiling, the 
hyperaccumulator plant 
<I>Thlaspi caerulescens
</I>, belongs to the same taxonomic family (Cruciferae) as 
<I>Arabidopsis thaliana
</I>. Because the 
<I>Arabidopsis
</I> genome has been completely sequenced recently, we can 
have a full benefit of those data for the identification of 
genes and proteins from 
<I>Thlaspi
</I>. The specific aim is to isolate and characterize 
putative genes and proteins conferring metal 
hyperaccumulation and tolerance traits. Interesting candidate 
genes are further examined for their function in yeast and 
<I>Arabidopsis
</I>.
</p>
<p>
<b>Unintended effects in genetically modified plants 
</b>
<br>One of the key issues in the risk assessment of GM crop 
plants is whether unexpected hazardous metabolic 
perturbations (so-called unintended effects) may have taken 
place in the plant due to genetic modification, affecting its 
safety as food or nutritional status. In the EU V Framework 
project GMOCARE our laboratory is responsible for the 
proteomics part of the work, some of which has been performed 
with genetically modified 
<I>Arabidopsis
</I> plants.
</p>
