<p>
<b>Signal Networks Controlling Adaptive Responses In Plants
</b>
<br>The long-term aim of our research is to elucidate the 
signal pathways and networks that control plant responses to 
environmental and developmental stimuli as well as ascribe 
the function of the key regulators as well as key response 
proteins and metabolites. 
</p>
<p>
<b>Cold acclimation.
</b> A central theme in our studies is to understand the 
molecular communication between higher plants and their 
environment using abiotic stresses (cold/drought and 
photoperiod) as models. The focus is on molecular analysis of 
cold acclimation in 
<I>Arabidopsis
</I>. 
<br>
<b>Plant-pathogen interaction.
</b> A major theme in this research is elucidation of signals 
and signal pathways involved in plant defense responses. Systemic genome 
wide analysis is currently employed to identify the central 
components of plant defense signaling and PCD development. 
Additionally we are focused on identification of plant 
receptors for the elicitors produced or released by the 
action of the pathogen by activation tagging.
<br>
<b>Cross talk between the signal pathways.
</b> Our current research is 
focused on characterizing some of the central nodes of stress signaling 
networks. These 
efforts are greatly facilitated by genetic and genomic 
techniques in particular using 
<I>Arabidopsis
</I> mutant collections, expression profiling and 
overexpression or RNAi silencing in transgenic plants.
</p>
 

